{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":30110,"record_hash":"sha256:7f003b5b715cd581c83a4d48e48fb1efa57ae6f499d5e70c012c6aa3d7939824","timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:29:02.342Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes. I’d think about this as a separate lifecycle layer above capture.\n\nRight now `but-agentlog` does only this:\n\n```text\nagent transcript -> redacted GitMeta SQLite state\n```\n\nThe GitMeta lifecycle adds:\n\n```text\nlocal SQLite -> serialize -> metadata commit/ref -> push\nremote metadata ref -> fetch -> materialize -> local SQLite\n```\n\nThat matches the spec pretty directly: serialize writes shareable metadata into Git commits/trees, and materialize turns incoming metadata trees back into local SQLite state. The host tool, GitButler in our case, decides when those happen and what is safe to share. See the GitMeta [workflow doc](https://git-meta.com/spec/implementation/workflow.html) and [materialization doc](https://git-meta.[REDACTED:entropy].html).\n\n**My current recommendation**\nKeep capture dumb. It should not push, serialize, fetch, or materialize.\n\nInstead, future GitButler lifecycle integration should own this:\n\n```text\nOutbound:\n  capture/hook writes local agentlog data\n  user pushes/syncs code\n  GitButler decides eligible metadata\n  git-meta serialize\n  push refs/meta/main or equivalent metadata ref\n\nInbound:\n  GitButler fetches/syncs code\n  fetch metadata refs\n  git-meta materialize\n  local agentlog reader queries SQLite\n```\n\nThat is good for our two use cases:\n\n```text\nSession handoff:\n  machine A captures -> serialize/push metadata\n  machine B fetches/materializes -> reader exposes session context\n\nReview context:\n  branch/PR association key is pushed\n  web/backend materializes metadata\n  UI resolves branch/PR -> session keys -> transcript records\n```\n\nThe most important product decision is not technical, it is privacy/policy: when do we publish `gitbutler:agent-session:*`? The keys are shareable-ready, but transcripts are still sensitive even after redaction. I would make first sharing explicit, or tied to a very clear GitButler action, not automatic on every hook capture.\n\nA few design notes I’d keep in mind:\n\n- `but-agentlog capture/hook` should stay local-only.\n- Metadata exchange belongs to a future `sync`/`push` integration, not the capture command.\n- Readers should query materialized SQLite, not Git trees directly.\n- On inbound materialize, consumers should still sort transcript records by fields, not trust list storage order.\n- On remote merge, duplicate semantic records are possible in theory, so future readers should dedupe by `record_hash` defensively.\n- Association keys become very important for review: branch/PR/change targets point to project session keys; transcript data remains project-scoped.\n\nSo the next concrete step I’d suggest is a short markdown design note for “Agentlog GitMeta Exchange Lifecycle” that documents this boundary before we touch code.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:29:02.342Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}